# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler & Toolchain (v5.6 arc)
# Optimization arc + regalloc arc, plus 5.6.30s stdlib/TLS/ABI/PP/heap-cap gotchas.
# 11 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_6_x_optimization_arc_gotchas_bundle"
description = "v5.6.0 — v5.6.17 gotchas: IR-pass debugging methodology, ESETCC IR-emit-order, parse_ctrl loop_top IR_NOP, IR_RAX_CLOBBER reads RCX, parse-time vs IR-time const-fold, NOP-fill preserves jumps, doc state-split (continued in v5_6_18_to_26_regalloc_arc_gotchas_bundle for Phase O4 + regalloc default-on)"
category = "cyrius"
---
=== IR-PASS BISECTION METHODOLOGY (v5.6.17 — load-bearing) ===

When an IR-walking pass (DCE, copy-prop, future peepholes) silently
corrupts cc5, do NOT keep guessing missing use/def cases by reading
code. The IR has too many opcodes and backend semantics to enumerate
from a desk read.

USE THIS PATTERN INSTEAD:

  1. Add a cap-env knob to the pass: CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP=N limits
     the pass to its first N actions. Default = -1 (uncapped).
     Implementation in src/common/ir.cyr:

       fn ir_pass_capped(S, cap) {
           var actions = 0;
           ...
           if (cap >= 0) { if (actions >= cap) { dead = 0; } }
           ...
           actions = actions + 1;
       }
       fn ir_pass(S) { return ir_pass_capped(S, 0 - 1); }

  2. Add a per-action context dump in the pass:

       <PASS> action #N ni=X op=OP a1=A1 a2=A2 | ctx:
         <-prev3 <-prev2 <-prev1 ->next1 ->next2 ->next3

     (Skip IR_NOP / IR_ELIMINATED in prev/next walk so dump shows
      real-instruction context, not whitespace.)

  3. Binary-search by varying CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP from 0 upward.
     Smallest N where cc5_b crashes = the action that's wrong.

  4. Inspect dump for action N. Opcode + 3 prev / 3 next ops will
     show the local pattern and what use/def case the pass missed.

WHY IT WORKS: the IR is small enough that 6 ops of context (3 each
side, NOP-filtered) shows the local pattern. The cap knob isolates
a single failing action so the dump output is manageable.

WHY GUESSING FAILED IN v5.6.16: two attempts at fixing DCE wasted
hours guessing missing-use cases (738 → 1,674 wrongly-killed
between attempts). v5.6.17 used the cap-knob methodology and found
the actual bug in ~10 minutes (kill #3 = MOV_CA before CLBRA).

KEEP THE KNOB: don't remove the cap env after the bug is fixed.
It's load-bearing for future audits when later passes (copy-prop,
dead-store, future peepholes) hit the same class of hidden semantic.

GENERALIZE: wire each new IR pass with its own cap on first
implementation, BEFORE turning the pass on. Const-fold could have
had CYRIUS_FOLD_CAP, copy-prop should have CYRIUS_COPYPROP_CAP, etc.

=== IR_RAX_CLOBBER READS RCX (v5.6.17 fix) ===

IR_RAX_CLOBBER is recorded by emit fns that mutate RAX (and possibly
RDX) without going through MOVR — specifically EMULH (mulh64),
EIDIV (idiv signed), ELODC (mov rax, [rcx]). The opcode name is
misleading — it doesn't ONLY clobber RAX. All three READ RCX:

  • EMULH:  reads rax, reads rcx, writes rax (hi half).
  • EIDIV:  reads rax (dividend low), reads rcx (divisor),
            writes rax (quotient), writes rdx (remainder).
  • ELODC:  reads rcx (the address), writes rax (the loaded value).

RCX is NEVER written by these — it's preserved across the op.

DCE liveness rules for IR_RAX_CLOBBER:
  • _ir_clobbers_rax(IR_RAX_CLOBBER) = 1   (writes rax)
  • _ir_uses_rax(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)     = 1   (reads rax — mulh/idiv)
  • _ir_def_rcx_any(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)  = 0   (does NOT write rcx)
  • _ir_uses_rcx(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)     = 1   (reads rcx — operand/divisor/address)

Same correction applies to:
  • IR_ADD_IMM_X1: rcx += imm — reads rcx, writes rcx. Both uses
    and def_rcx_any. Use case in PE arg-shuttle path.
  • IR_RAW_EMIT (v5.6.12 marker): opaque conservative — could read
    OR write any register. Treat as both reader and writer for
    RAX and RCX so DCE can't kill anything around it.

If you forget any of these correspondences, DCE will kill an
upstream MOV_CA whose RCX value the CLBRA needed.

=== ESETCC IR-EMIT-ORDER RULE (v5.6.15) ===

When an emit helper (Efoo) calls another emit helper (Ebar), and
both record their own IR opcodes via _IR_REC*, the order in which
they record matters. The IR stream must mirror the BYTE order in
codebuf — not the source-line order in the helper.

WRONG (IR says SETCC→CMP, bytes are cmp→setcc):

  fn ESETCC(S, op) {
      if (_IR_REC1(S, IR_SETCC, op) == 1) { return 0; }
      ECMPR(S);   # this records IR_CMP after we already recorded SETCC
      EB(S, 0x0F); ...
  }

RIGHT (IR matches byte order):

  fn ESETCC(S, op) {
      ECMPR(S);
      if (_IR_REC1(S, IR_SETCC, op) == 1) { return 0; }
      EB(S, 0x0F); ...
  }

WHY IT MATTERS: at IR_ENABLED=0 the bug is silent (IR not consumed).
At IR_ENABLED ≥ 1, any pass walking adjacent IR ops (peephole match,
liveness, dead-code) sees inverted order and either misses real
fusions or misclassifies live-ranges. v5.6.15 found 3,665 SETCC→CMP
IR adjacencies that were really cmp→setcc in bytes.

AUDIT RULE: every emit fn that calls another emit fn must record IR
AFTER the sub-call, not before. The IR sequence should read top-to-
bottom in the same order codebuf bytes appear.

=== PARSE_CTRL LOOP_TOP IR_NOP REQUIREMENT (v5.6.14) ===

When parse captures `loop_top = GCP(S)` for a back-edge target
(while/for/for-in/classic-for), it MUST also record an IR_NOP at
that position with arg1=loop_top:

  loop_top = GCP(S);
  if (_ire >= 1) { ir_emit(S, IR_NOP, 0, loop_top, 0); }

Without the IR_NOP marker, ir_build_bbs doesn't see a BB boundary
at the loop entry. JMP_BACK edges then land mid-BB, and any pass
that reasons about per-BB state (LASE, future copy-prop) will
incorrectly conclude that values from the BB's first-entry path
are still live during loop iterations.

v5.6.14 found this when re-enabling LASE: 811 LOAD_LOCAL eliminations
that all looked correct turned into 5,692 B of corruption because
the LOAD was redundant on first iteration but not on second.

PATTERN GENERALIZES: any back-edge target needs an IR_NOP landing
pad. Forward-jump targets (EPATCH) already get NOP markers via the
existing patch convention.

=== PARSE-TIME VS IR-TIME CONST-FOLD (v5.6.16) ===

Cyrius has TWO const-fold mechanisms now:

  1. PARSE-TIME via _cfo / _cfv flags in parse_expr.cyr
     Tracks single-side-literal fold: `5 * x`, `a + 7`, etc.
     Fires when LHS is a literal (`_cfo == 1`) and RHS is also
     a NUM token. Bytes-perfect in-place rewrite — uses SCP() to
     rewind CP and re-emit EMOVI(folded_val).

  2. IR-TIME via ir_const_fold() in ir.cyr (v5.6.16)
     Forward state-machine sweep over IR for the patterns parse-
     time missed: LOAD_IMM(a), PUSH, LOAD_IMM(b), [POP_RCX |
     MOV_CA + POP_RAX], OP. Two shapes covered (commutative
     after v5.6.10 shuttle elim, non-commutative). For each
     match: in-place rewrite codebuf — write EMOVI(fold_val) at
     LHS LOAD_IMM CP, NOP-fill remainder of span. Mark consumed
     IR nodes IR_NOP to keep IR consistent.

When to use which:

  • Parse-time is the right place when LHS is known literal at
    parse time (typical case). It rewinds CP — bytes shrink.
  • IR-time catches the long tail (e.g., when LHS comes from a
    fold that itself wasn't possible at parse-time, or when
    PARSE_TERM took a non-fold branch due to precedence). It
    rewrites in-place — bytes preserved (NOP-filled), real
    shrinkage waits for v5.6.22 codebuf compaction.

DON'T duplicate work: the IR pass should not re-detect what
parse-time already handled. v5.6.16 measurement: 130 IR folds vs
hundreds of parse-time folds — the IR pass is genuinely the long
tail.

=== NOP-FILL PRESERVES JUMP TARGETS + FIXUPS (v5.6.16 design choice) ===

All v5.6.x IR-level optimizations (LASE, const-fold, DCE, future
copy-prop) NOP-fill bytes in the codebuf rather than rewinding CP.
This is intentional:

  • Forward jumps (EPATCH) reference target offsets relative to
    end-of-jump-instruction. If we shifted bytes, we'd have to
    rewalk and patch every jump.
  • Backward jumps (JMP_BACK) similarly reference prior CPs.
  • The fixup table (FIXUP() at end of compile) references node
    CPs. Shifting would invalidate the table.
  • IR_NODE_CP records would need rebuilding.

NOP-fill sidesteps all of this — bytes don't move, jumps stay valid,
fixups still resolve. The cost: cc5 binary stays the same total size,
just with more 0x90 bytes. NOPs are decoded at near-zero µop cost on
modern CPUs, so runtime is unaffected.

REAL BINARY SHRINKAGE waits for v5.6.22 codebuf compaction — a single
pass at end of pipeline that:
  1. Walks codebuf for runs of ≥4 NOPs
  2. CP-rewinds past the run
  3. Shifts subsequent code down
  4. Fixes up forward jumps + fixup table CPs + IR_NODE_CP records

Doing compaction at end consolidates the work — one pass instead of
per-optimization. Plus jump+fixup repair is non-trivial; better to
get it right once than per-pass.

=== STATE-DOC SPLIT (v5.6.16 — process meta-lesson) ===

CLAUDE.md's "Current State" paragraph grew to 32 KB on a single line
because every release appended another sentence. Made it
unmaintainable for ingestion (token cost, parsability) and prone to
silent rot (version refs duplicated in 4 places).

THE FIX: split CLAUDE.md into preferences/process/procedures (durable,
~150 lines) + docs/development/state.md (volatile, refreshed every
release, ~50 lines). Historical narrative goes in
docs/development/completed-phases.md.

PATTERN GENERALIZES: any project's "instructions" doc that includes
"current state" is at risk. Watch for the rot:

  • A "Current State" or "Recent Changes" section that grows by
    one sentence per release.
  • Version numbers duplicated across multiple sections of the
    same doc.
  • Aspirational/historical content interleaved with durable rules.

When you see this pattern, propose a split. Durable rules in the
top-level instruction file; volatile state in a sibling refreshed-
per-release doc. The instruction file becomes preferences/process/
procedures only.

=== ROADMAP QUALITY-BEFORE-OPS RULE (v5.6.16/17 enforced) ===

When an optimization pass corrupts cc5 even after audit attempts,
SHIP what works correctly and BAIL on the broken piece. Don't
force in something that doesn't work just to hit a pre-planned slot.

v5.6.16 example: planned to ship const-fold + bitmap liveness + DCE
together (~260 LOC). Const-fold worked clean (130 folds / 774 B);
DCE corrupted cc5. Shipped const-fold alone, bailed on DCE,
re-pinned to v5.6.17 with proper investigation budget. v5.6.17 used
the bisection methodology (which itself became a saved pattern),
fixed in ~10 min, shipped clean (678 kills / 2,010 B).

THE BAD ALTERNATIVE: would have been to either ship broken DCE
(NOPE — cc5 wouldn't self-host), OR keep desk-reading missing-use
cases for hours/days (already failed twice in v5.6.16). The bisection
methodology was the third option that surfaced because of "STOP and
ask" — when stuck, propose both the small ship and the bigger fix.

DON'T SLIP UNILATERALLY: pinning the deferred half to a specific next
slot (v5.6.17, v5.6.18) is the user's call, not yours. Report
findings, propose options, wait for direction. The cascade is
acceptable IF the bug fix justifies its own slot — which it does for
correctness work.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_6_18_to_26_regalloc_arc_gotchas_bundle"
description = "v5.6.18 — v5.6.26 gotchas: regalloc default-on, Phase O4 split, SysV ECALLPOPS r12-r14 clobber, asm/regalloc layout collision, picker bisection methodology, EPOPARG cancel-mirror gap, Phase O5 maximal-munch dead end"
category = "cyrius"
---
v5.6.18 → v5.6.26 covered the optimization arc's Phase O4 (regalloc)
landing — including default-on flip — plus the v5.6.25 aarch64
push/pop-cancel completion that closed v5.6.11's mirror gap. Phase
O5 maximal-munch was tried at v5.6.26 scope but dropped (recon
found 0 fused-op candidates; push-imm rewrite has rax-side-effect +
forward-jump-target issues; needs an IR-level push-elision pass
first).

=== CODEGEN SCRATCH REGS MUST BE CALLER-SAVED (v5.6.24) ===

The biggest landmine in the regalloc default-on landing.
`src/backend/x86/emit.cyr::ECALLPOPS` SysV n>6 stack-arg shuttle
used **r12, r13, r14 as scratch** to pop extras across the 6
reg-arg pops. r11 was correctly caller-saved; r12-r14 are
CALLEE-SAVED in SysV. Pre-regalloc, that was safe-by-accident
because cyrius didn't emit r12-r15 anywhere. Once v5.6.20+
regalloc started pinning caller's locals to those exact
callee-saved regs, every 8+ arg call silently corrupted the
locals — caller's pinned `fs` was overwritten with a popped arg
value before the call, callee preserved (the wrong) value, and
the caller continued with garbage.

Surfaced as TWO bisection-disjoint reports:
1. flags.tcyr at AUTO_CAP=118 — the 118th auto-enabled fn
   (`test_str_short`) had an `_argv(3, "prog", "-o", "/tmp/out.s",
   0, 0, 0, 0, 0)` 9-arg call; the shuttle clobbered r12 holding
   `fs` in the next-fn `test_defaults`'s frame; flags_get_int
   returned 0 instead of the registered default 7.
2. sandhi M2 (filed 2026-04-24, same date-case file) —
   sandhi_http_response_parse's `var headers` silently zeroed by
   an unrelated downstream call. Workaround was
   `var hdr_backup = headers;` (shifted local layout away from
   picker's choice).

Same root. Fix: rewrote SysV ECALLPOPS to use **only r10
(caller-saved)** via direct `[rsp+offset]` MOV addressing — no
pops, single shift loop, end with `add rsp, 48`. Length-equal to
the un-rewritten path.

**Audit rule for new codegen** (load-bearing): any register used
as scratch in cyrius codegen MUST be caller-saved in the target
ABI, OR be explicitly saved/restored. SysV caller-saved scratch:
rax/rcx/rdx/rsi/rdi/r8/r9/r10/r11. Win64 caller-saved scratch:
rax/rcx/rdx/r8/r9/r10/r11. Avoid rbx/r12-r15 unless wrapping with
push+pop pairs (and accounting for the rsp shift in nearby
[rsp+N] references).

=== "ALIGNMENT REGRESSION" CAN BE A RED HERRING (v5.6.23) ===

v5.6.22's default-on flip surfaced what looked like a v5.5.21
array-alignment regression — `regression-inline-asm-discard.sh`
SIGSEGV'd on PXOR xmm,m128 over `var rk[240]`. The shape said
"alignment". v5.6.23 investigation had to PROBE the array VA
(`mod 16 = 0` — fine) before discarding the alignment framing.

Real cause: `regalloc's prologue saves rbx/r12-r15 to [rbp-8]..
[rbp-40]`, and `parse_fn.cyr` computes local-var disps as
`-(idx + 1 + _cur_fn_regalloc) * 8`, shifting every spilled
local/param 40 B further from rbp. Inline asm hardcodes
`mov rdi, [rbp-0x08]` to read param 1 under the standard cyrius
prologue. Under auto-enable that read the saved RBX value (a
pointer-shaped garbage) which PXOR then dereferenced.

Fix: `parse_fn.cyr` body-scan lookahead for token 48 (`asm`).
Auto-enable silently skips fns with asm; opt-in `#regalloc`
on an asm fn warns and skips. Stdlib callers protected:
`lib/fnptr.cyr`, `lib/thread.cyr`, `lib/atomic.cyr`,
`lib/hashmap_fast.cyr`, `lib/u128.cyr`, `lib/thread_local.cyr`,
`lib/fdlopen.cyr`, `lib/args_macos.cyr`.

**Generalized rule**: when symptom is a memop SIGSEGV under new
codegen and the obvious culprit looks like an existing fix's
edge case, probe the operand's actual address FIRST. If the
alignment/size/value is correct, the bug is elsewhere in the
pipeline — usually layout or register choice.

=== PICKER TIME-SHARE BREAKS LOOPS (v5.6.22) ===

v5.6.20's Poletto-Sarkar picker added time-sliced register reuse:
when an interval expires, its register can be reassigned to a
later interval. SAFE for straight-line forward execution. UNSAFE
for any backward CFG edge (loops): JMP_BACK to a position INSIDE
an EARLIER interval re-reads the register expecting the earlier
value but finds the new (time-shared) one.

Surfaced at v5.6.22 auto-enable bisection on
`PP_ALREADY_INCLUDED`'s nested while loops:
- rbx assigned to `cnt` for [135876, 135900] — covered the
  `while (i < cnt)` condition LOAD inside the outer loop
- After lidx=2 expired, rbx reassigned to `p` for [135963, 136057]
- Outer loop iteration JMP_BACK re-executed the cnt LOAD at
  CP 135900 — but rbx now held `p`'s value
- Wrong loop count → infinite loop / wrong branch

**Fix**: extend `interval.last_cp = ra_end` for every interval —
picker can no longer time-share registers (intervals never expire
before fn end). Effectively single-register-per-local-for-whole-fn
= greedy-equivalent. Proper time-sharing needs cross-BB liveness
analysis (extend last_cp through backward CFG edges) — pinned
future slot.

=== PHASE O4 SPLIT (v5.6.19/20/22 — 1→3 slots) ===

Originally pinned as full Poletto-Sarkar linear-scan in one slot
(~600-900 LOC). Structural reality: no vreg layer, no cross-BB
liveness, every emit fn hardcoded RAX/RCX. Made one-slot
infeasible. Split into:
- v5.6.19 = Phase O4a: per-fn live-interval infra (ra_first/ra_last
  arrays, dump knob). Ships intervals; no codegen change. Also
  fixed a pre-existing v4.8.4 latent sizing bug — `ra_counts[256]`
  was 256 BYTES (32 i64 slots) but write loop wrote 256 i64s;
  overflow into adjacent global memory; existing peephole tolerated
  it because high-idx use-counts default to 0; interval tracking
  needed correct sizing.
- v5.6.20 = Phase O4b: Poletto-Sarkar picker. Replaces v4.8.4
  greedy use-count picker. Insertion-sort intervals by first_cp
  (deterministic tie-break by lidx), walk forward, expire active
  intervals, assign free reg or spill furthest-next-use.
  CYRIUS_REGALLOC_PICKER_CAP=N from day 1 for bisection.
- v5.6.22 = Phase O4c (partial): auto-enable infra DISABLED by
  default + picker correctness fix (loop-back time-share — extend
  last_cp = ra_end). Default-on attempt at this slot surfaced two
  bugs: (1) inline-asm layout collision (fixed v5.6.23); (2) ECALLPOPS
  r12-r14 clobber (fixed v5.6.24).
- v5.6.24 = default-on flip + the ECALLPOPS rewrite.

**Lesson**: when a pinned slot is structurally infeasible after recon,
SPLIT into legitimate phases (cascading +N is fine) rather than
band-aiding or scope-cutting. Bandaids/threshold tweaks/auto-enable+
patch are shortcuts. Splits are pre-planned decompositions.

=== EPOPARG MIRROR GAP (v5.6.25 — aarch64 push/pop-cancel completion) ===

v5.6.9 shipped push/pop-cancel for x86 (381 pairs eliminated).
v5.6.11's memory said "aarch64 mirror fires too" — but only the
EPOPR path. EPOPARG(S, n) emits the SAME `ldr xN, [sp], #16` for
N=0..7. For N=0 the encoding is identical to EPOPR's pop-x0
(0xF84107E0). EPOPR did the v5.6.9 adjacency check; EPOPARG
DIDN'T. Every 1-arg call site (EPUSHR; ECALLPOPS(1) → EPOPARG(S, 0))
paid 8 bytes of redundant push+pop.

Bytescan recon under v5.6.24 default-on regalloc found 2,569 such
pairs in native aarch64 cc5. 13-LOC fix in EPOPARG mirroring
EPOPR's `GCP == _last_push_cp` rewind, gated on `n == 0`. Native
aarch64 cc5 **517,376 → 497,008 B (−20,368 B / −3.94%)** — bigger
than v5.6.11's combine-shuttle shrinkage.

**Audit pattern when reusing a documented optimization**: when an
existing fix is documented as "also fires for X", verify ALL emit
paths for X — not just the primary one. Mirror-gap bugs hide in
the secondary paths that nobody re-audited.

=== PHASE O5 MAXIMAL-MUNCH DEAD END (v5.6.26-attempted, dropped) ===

Phase O5 was originally pinned for v5.6.26 (after Phase O4
regalloc landed). Goal: fuse adjacent operations into single
instructions (mul+add → MADD on aarch64; mov-imm + push →
push-imm on x86). Recon under v5.6.24 default-on regalloc:
- aarch64 mul+add adjacent pairs: **0** across cc5_native_arm + 8
  math-heavy tcyr tests (bigint, u128, mulh64, keccak, sha1, base64,
  hashmap, vec). cyrius's stack-machine IR keeps a `str x0, [sp,
  #-16]!` between every sub-expression result and consumer, so
  `mul+add` pairs are SEPARATED by push/pop pairs. Fusion window
  doesn't open without a separate IR-level push-elision pass.
- x86 push-imm fusion (`mov eax, imm32; push rax` → `push imm32`):
  2,861 sites in cc5 (recon), but rewriting fails because EMOVI
  has a SIDE EFFECT (sets rax = imm) that subsequent code may
  read. Forward jumps patched by EPATCH land at the post-EMOVI
  position; rewriting changes what's at that position semantically.
  ~71% of sites have ambiguous rax usage by conservative heuristic.

**Pinned long-term, no slot**. Both branches need an IR-level
push-elision pass to make the fusion windows actually open. v5.6.26
shipped peephole refinement + doc completion instead.

=== BISECTION METHODOLOGY (saved v5.6.17, used v5.6.22 + v5.6.24) ===

The v5.6.17 IR-pass bisection pattern (CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP=N env knob
+ binary-search) keeps paying dividends. v5.6.22 used
CYRIUS_REGALLOC_AUTO_CAP=N + CYRIUS_REGALLOC_PICKER_CAP=N to
narrow time-share bug to "PP_ALREADY_INCLUDED + 3rd reassignment"
in ~10 minutes. v5.6.24 used the same knob to narrow the
ECALLPOPS bug to "test_str_short = 118th auto-enabled fn + its
9-arg _argv call". Both saved hours.

**Pattern for new codegen passes**: ship a CAP env knob in the
SAME slot as the pass itself, not later. Costs ~5 LOC, makes
bisection trivial when something breaks.

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_alloc_grow_step_vs_requested_size"
description = "Bump-allocator grow logic must cover the requested allocation, not a fixed delta — fixed step `0x100000` regardless of requested size returned pointers past the brk/mmap for any alloc(>1MB)"
category = "cyrius"
---
BUG SHAPE: The cyrius stdlib bump allocator (`lib/alloc.cyr`,
`lib/alloc_macos.cyr`) grew the heap by exactly `0x100000`
whenever `_heap_ptr` crossed `_heap_end`, regardless of how far
past the new pointer was. Any single `alloc(size > 1 MB)` near
the grow boundary returned a pointer past the newly-mapped
region — `alloc()` reported success, and the caller's first
tail-write SIGSEGV'd at an unmapped address.

Pre-fix (Linux brk path):
    _heap_ptr = new_ptr;
    if (_heap_ptr > _heap_end) {
        var new_end = _heap_end + 0x100000;   // fixed delta
        var result = syscall(12, new_end);
        ...
        _heap_end = new_end;
    }
    return ptr;                                // past new _heap_end

Post-fix (v5.6.34 Linux):
    var new_end = (_heap_ptr + 0xFFFFF) & (0 - 0x100000);
    // round up to next 1MB grain; one brk per grow covers any size

Post-fix (v5.6.34 macOS):
    while (_heap_end < _heap_ptr) {
        // loop 1MB mmaps; preserves per-step contiguity guard
        // (a single hinted mmap can legitimately return a
        // different base for larger requests)
    }

WHERE IT BIT: sit v0.6.1 S-33 triage. The 16 MiB zlib retry
buffer in `object_db.cyr:read_object` allocates in one call
via `alloc(16 * 1024 * 1024)`. On a 100-commit fixture, the
grow boundary fell inside this allocation — SIGSEGV on first
write into the tail past the 1 MB mapped region.

BROADER LESSON: any bump-allocator grow step must compare
against the requested allocation size, not a hardcoded delta.
The fixed-step pattern is fine ONLY when the hot path is
known to be many small allocations; the moment a consumer
does one large allocation, the pattern silently miscompiles
into returned-pointer-past-mapped-region.

DETECTION: `tests/tcyr/alloc_grow.tcyr` covers this directly
(4 MB + 16 MB tail-writes + 1000×64 B after jumbos + 128 MB
single block). Extend when adding new alloc paths.

RELATED LATENT SUSPECT: sit's same 2026-04-24 ticket reports
a second symptom — `sit fsck` reports ~20% of objects
unreadable after the grow fix — which MAY be a different
cyrius stdlib memory-corruption mode (stale pointer /
double-commit in the bump allocator beyond the grow bug),
or a dep-layer bug (patra / sankoch). Pinned as v5.6.35
triage; do not assume it's a cyrius bug without the
prescribed patra bytes-roundtrip + sankoch symmetry first.

[[entries]]
name = "sit_symptom_2_was_sankoch_encoder_not_cyrius"
description = "v5.6.35 — sit's 'fsck reports unreadable objects at scale' was a sankoch deflate encoder bug, not a cyrius alloc bug. Triage methodology that pinned it: standalone replay of dumped buffers + in-process roundtrip instrumentation + per-row checksum around dep boundary calls."
category = "cyrius"
---
PROBLEM SHAPE: sit reported "after fixing the alloc grow bug,
20% of objects come back unreadable at scale, first bad at ~commit
15, scales with N." Three plausible layers (patra / sankoch /
cyrius latent corruption) — fix-before-triage forbidden.

WHAT THE TRIAGE LOOKED LIKE (cyrius v5.6.35):

1. Reproduce the failure end-to-end. Build sit against current
   cyrius + deps, run the 100-commit fixture, confirm the
   reported failure rate (53/247 unreadable on the documented
   fixture).

2. Eliminate patra: write a standalone cyrius program that
   exercises patra with sit-shaped row inserts (STR + INT +
   BYTES schema) at the failure scale. 1600+ rows across
   single-process, cross-session (close+reopen), query-then-
   insert, and cross-process patterns — all clean. Rules out
   patra.

3. Eliminate cyrius alloc: instrument sit's `write_typed_object`
   with a pre/post checksum of the `compressed` buffer around
   the `patra_insert_row` call. Match across all 300 inserts
   means the buffer isn't being mutated in transit. Rules out
   in-call buffer mutation by the dep boundary.

4. Eliminate sit-side aliasing: in the same sit instrumentation,
   add an in-process `zlib_decompress(compressed, clen, ...)`
   immediately after `zlib_compress` returns the positive
   `clen`. If THAT fails (50/300 did) — bug is in the encoder
   for those specific inputs, not in any post-encoder buffer
   handling.

5. Confirm input-determinism: dump every `<hash>.full` and
   `<hash>.cz` to sidecar files. Replay each `.full` through
   sankoch in a fresh process (no patra, no sit, no cyrius
   pressure). 50/300 fail standalone with byte-identical output
   to what sit produced. Encoder is deterministic on input.

6. Save the smallest failing input as a minimal repro
   (~50-line standalone cyrius program reading the bytes from
   stdin and asserting roundtrip). Hand off to sankoch.

WHAT IT WASN'T:
- Not patra. patra ROUNDTRIPS bytes correctly.
- Not cyrius alloc. v5.6.34's grow fix was sufficient for
  alloc-side correctness; the 50/300 failures persist with
  v5.6.34's fix in place.
- Not sit-side. Sit passes the right buffer + length to patra;
  the buffer isn't mutated in transit; the buffer can't be
  decompressed even microseconds after compress returns in the
  same process under the same lock.

WHY THE BUG DIDN'T SHOW IN SANKOCH'S OWN TEST SUITE: sankoch's
roundtrip tests use synthetic byte patterns (random fills,
text-like fills) that don't trigger the bad symbol distribution
the encoder mishandles. The bug needed sit's tree-object byte
shape (mix of `100644 file_<i>.txt\0` ASCII + 32-byte binary
hashes per entry) at specific lengths to surface. Lesson: a
roundtrip-test-corpus that doesn't include real consumer-shape
inputs has dead spots.

RESOLUTION: 3 sankoch tags (2.0.1 → 2.0.2 fixed 51/53; 2.0.3
fixed remaining 2). Cyrius v5.6.35 = dep-pin bump 2.0.1 → 2.0.3
in `cyrius.cyml` + active `tests/regression-sit-status.sh` gate.

GENERALIZE: when triaging a "consumer X reports issue Y at
scale" against a stack of deps, the dump-and-replay pattern
turns multi-layer state-interaction bugs into single-layer
deterministic repros. Save: input-to-suspect, output-of-suspect,
and the calling-program's pre/post state if relevant. Replay
each in isolation. The layer that reproduces the failure with
NONE of the calling state is the layer that owns the bug.

[[entries]]
name = "two_consecutive_platform_drift_pins_were_both_fn_main_fixture_bugs"
description = "v5.6.33 (Mach-O) and v5.6.36 (PE) — two consecutive 'platform drift' regression pins on cyrius's roadmap turned out to be the SAME test-fixture bug, not actual compiler regressions"
category = "cyrius"
---
PATTERN OBSERVED: v5.6.33 and v5.6.36 were both pinned as
"platform drift" regressions — Mach-O syscall(60,42) exits 1 not
42 on macOS Sequoia (v5.6.33), PE syscall(60,42) exits 0x40010080
not 42 on Win11 24H2 (v5.6.36). Both attributed to OS loader
hardening (Sequoia dyld strictness, 24H2 CET shadow-stack /
DllCharacteristics enforcement). Both turned out to be the SAME
test-fixture bug.

THE FIXTURE BUG: each gate's source used
  fn main() { syscall(60, 42); return 0; }

In cyrius this is a function definition that is NEVER CALLED.
There is no auto-invoked `main()`. Top-level statements ARE the
program entry. With no top-level code, the entry prologue's
branch-over-fn-bodies (patched by `EJMP0`/`EPATCH`) lands on the
EEXIT/EEXIT_PE tail, which calls the platform's exit routine with
whatever happened to be in the arg-slot register / x0:
- macOS arm64: BSD `_exit(x0)` — x0 = argc (= 1 from shell) → rc=1.
- Linux x86_64: `exit(rax)` syscall — rax content varies.
- Windows PE: `kernel32!ExitProcess(rcx)` — rcx may have inherited
  state from runtime, on Win11 24H2 it landed on 0x40010080 (an
  NTSTATUS-shape value with high-nibble 0x4 =
  STATUS_SEVERITY_INFORMATIONAL, which made PowerShell report
  `ApplicationFailedException` instead of a plain non-zero
  exit code).

THE 30-SECOND CHECK that disproves both:
  $ cat <<EOF | cc5 > /tmp/probe; chmod +x /tmp/probe
  syscall(60, 42);
  EOF
  $ /tmp/probe; echo $?
  42

If THAT exits 42, the platform/loader/codegen is fine and the
gate's `fn main()` fixture is the only bug.

V5.6.36 ALSO VERIFIED: on Win11 24H2, patching the cyrius-
emitted PE's DllCharacteristics from 0x0000 (no flags) →
0x0160 (DYNAMIC_BASE | NX_COMPAT | HIGH_ENTROPY_VA) produced
byte-identical exit behavior — both forms exit 42 with the
corrected source, both exit 0x40010080 with the broken source.
**Win11 24H2 does NOT require security flags.** That whole
suspect class was wrong.

GENERALIZED RULE (already in feedback memory
`feedback_verify_slot_premise_first.md`): when triaging
"platform drift since vX.Y.Z" reports for cyrius, FIRST
verify the test fixture exercises what it claims to test.
The 30-second top-level-syntax probe is cheaper than ANY
investigation premise based on the broken fixture.

WHY IT KEPT HAPPENING: gate fixture authors who came from C/Rust
backgrounds wrote `fn main()` assuming entry-point convention
that doesn't exist in cyrius. The same pattern bit two
consecutive gate authors. v5.6.33 and v5.6.36 both ship with the
fixture rewrite + a CHANGELOG paragraph explicitly documenting
the misdiagnosis class.

PINNED FOR FUTURE: when adding a regression gate that needs to
"return value N from a cyrius program", use `syscall(60, N)` at
top level, not `fn main() { syscall(60, N); return 0; }`. If the
gate needs a helper function, define it then call it from
top-level:
  fn add3(a, b, c) { return a + b + c; }
  syscall(60, add3(10, 20, 12));

[[entries]]
name = "libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open"
description = "v5.6.37 — libssl's OPENSSL_init_ssl uses a recursive pthread mutex whose __kind field lives in the glibc TCB. cyrius's dynlib_bootstrap_tls zeroed TCB reads __kind=0 (non-recursive); same-thread re-entry deadlocks on futex."
category = "cyrius"
---
WHAT BREAKS: pre-v5.6.37 `lib/tls.cyr::_tls_init` loaded libssl
via `dynlib_open` on top of `dynlib_bootstrap_tls`'s 4096-byte
zeroed TCB + `arch_prctl(ARCH_SET_FS)`. That's enough for
`%fs:N` reads and IFUNC resolvers. It is NOT enough for libssl.

libssl 3's `OPENSSL_init_ssl` uses a recursive pthread mutex
inside the glibc TCB. The mutex's `__kind` field (offset varies
by glibc version, but it's in the TCB region) determines
whether a same-thread re-entry is legal. On a real
glibc-initialised process, `__kind = PTHREAD_MUTEX_RECURSIVE_NP`
(= 1) because `__libc_pthread_init` set it. On cyrius's zeroed
stub, `__kind = 0 = PTHREAD_MUTEX_TIMED_NP` (non-recursive).
libssl re-enters → CAS 0→1 (acquire), CAS 0→1 fails (already
held), CAS 1→2 (mark contended), `futex(mutex, WAIT, 2, NULL)`.
Single-threaded process → nothing wakes it → indefinite hang.

Symptom: `strace` shows
`futex(0x??cc118, FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE, 2, NULL)` with no
subsequent syscalls. The futex address falls inside cyrius's
bump heap (same range as `dynlib_bootstrap_tls`'s TCB).

FIX (shipped v5.6.37): route libssl through `fdlopen`, not
`dynlib_open`. `fdlopen_init_full` invokes
`~/.cyrius/dlopen-helper` through the real
`ld-linux-x86-64.so.2`, which runs `_dl_start` +
`__libc_start_main` + full `__libc_pthread_init`. By the
time control returns to cyrius, the process has a
fully-initialised glibc TCB (DTV, stack_guard,
pthread_kind, `__libc_multiple_threads`, the whole set).
Subsequent `dlopen("libssl.so.3")` (via
`fdlopen_dlopen(state)`) loads libssl against real glibc;
all pthread primitives work.

WHEN YOU NEED FDLOPEN VS DYNLIB:
- **Use `dynlib_open`** for libraries whose symbols cyrius
  calls but that don't need real pthread state — libresolv
  for DNS lookups, libcrypto for isolated hash/AES calls
  (no init_ssl-style recursive mutex), libsystemd for
  journal writes, etc.
- **Use `fdlopen_dlopen`** for libraries that use pthread
  primitives as part of their own init — libssl, libpq,
  libcurl, anything that calls `pthread_once` /
  `pthread_mutex_lock` with recursive expectation during
  startup. If you're not sure, fdlopen is safe; dynlib is
  faster but brittle.

CONSUMER REQUIREMENT (v5.6.37+): `lib/tls.cyr` no longer
auto-includes `lib/fdlopen.cyr` because cyrius's preprocessor
expanded-output cap is 1 MB and heavy stdlib consumers
(`tests/tcyr/large_input.tcyr`) already run at 98%. Callers
of `lib/tls.cyr` MUST include fdlopen.cyr first:

    include "lib/fdlopen.cyr"   # ← required as of v5.6.37
    include "lib/tls.cyr"

Without the fdlopen include, cc5 warns about undefined
functions (`fdlopen_helper_available`, `fdlopen_init_full`,
etc.) and the binary SIGILLs on the first `tls_available()`
call.

DEBUGGING PATTERN FOR FUTURE PTHREAD-STUB-DEADLOCK BUGS:
1. `strace -f` the hanging program. Find the last futex
   with no subsequent syscalls.
2. Match the futex address against `/proc/<pid>/maps`.
3. If it falls inside cyrius's bump heap (TCB region), the
   library's pthread primitive is using stub-TCB state.
4. The fix is either (a) extend the stub to cover whatever
   field the library reads, or (b) switch to fdlopen so the
   library gets a real glibc.
5. (a) is version-specific and fragile; (b) works once the
   fdlopen helper is installed.

[[entries]]
name = "version_string_must_not_be_hardcoded_in_source"
description = "v5.6.39 — cc5 --version drifted at 5.6.29-1 for 9 releases because the version was hardcoded in src/main.cyr and version-bump.sh's regex didn't match the -N hotfix suffix. Fix: route through auto-generated src/version_str.cyr; never hardcode versions in source."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: any version string baked at compile time MUST come from
an auto-generated file the bump script writes via heredoc, NOT
from a hardcoded source literal updated via regex sed.

WHY: the regex shape is brittle to suffix conventions. cyrius's
version-bump.sh used a grep gate:

    grep -Eq '"cc5 [0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\\n"' src/main.cyr

That matches `X.Y.Z\n` but not `X.Y.Z-N\n`. When v5.6.29-1
shipped (hotfix suffix per the documented `-N` convention),
the literal `"cc5 5.6.29-1\n"` no longer matched the gate.
The grep returned empty, the sed was skipped, and the bump
emitted `warning: no cc5 version string found in src/main.cyr`
to stderr — silently logged, never escalated. The bump
"succeeded" but the literal stayed at 5.6.29-1. Subsequent
9 bumps repeated the same silent failure. `cc5 --version`
got stuck at `5.6.29-1` until a USER caught it via Starship
prompt observation.

`src/main_win.cyr` had the same bug shape with WORSE drift:
the bumper only ever swept `main.cyr`, never `main_win.cyr`,
so `cc5_win --version` had been stuck at `5.5.0` since
v5.5.0 ever shipped.

WRONG FIX: extend the regex to `[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+(-[0-9]+)?\\n`
to accept the `-N` suffix. Re-introduces the same bug class
for any future suffix shape (`-rc1`, `-pre`, `-alpha2`,
date-stamp suffixes, etc.). The bug class is "version string
in source = brittle".

RIGHT FIX (shipped v5.6.39): eliminate hardcoded literals.
Generate `src/version_str.cyr` from `VERSION` via heredoc.
Sources `include` the generated file and reference vars.
No regex, no per-file sweeping, no suffix vulnerability.

GENERALIZED RULE: any time a build script's job is to "rewrite
a literal in source", consider whether the literal can be
moved to a generated include file instead. Generated files
are simple (heredoc, single-pass write); regex-rewriting
literals is a fragile pattern that drifts silently the moment
the source format violates the regex's assumptions.

DETECTION (look for these patterns when triaging build-script
issues):

    if grep -Eq 'PATTERN' source-file; then
        sed -i ...
    else
        echo "warning: pattern not found"
    fi

This shape is the silent-drift recipe. Replace with:

    cat > generated-file <<EOF
    var X = "$NEW";
    var X_LEN = ${#NEW};
    EOF

And `include` the generated file from the source.

BUMP SCRIPT MUST REGENERATE ON SAME-VERSION INVOCATION too —
otherwise the documented "regenerate without bumping" path
silently no-ops. cyrius's version-bump.sh moves the
`src/version_str.cyr` write BEFORE the
`if [ "$NEW" = "$OLD" ]; then exit 0; fi` early-exit gate.

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_tls_hook_surface_via_fn_pointer_not_callback_registry"
description = "v5.6.40 — lib/tls.cyr exposes ALPN/mTLS via tls_connect_with_ctx_hook(sock, host, hook_fp, hook_ctx) + tls_dlsym(name) instead of registering callbacks per concern (set_alpn / set_verify / set_cert). One hook fn-pointer + one symbol-resolver = bounded surface; consumers compose freely."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a stdlib module wraps a C library that exposes
N configuration knobs (ALPN, mTLS, verify cb, session
tickets, SNI override, ...), do NOT mirror N knobs into
the stdlib API. Expose ONE pre-handshake hook that runs on
the underlying object, plus ONE symbol-resolver that hands
the consumer the raw C function pointers from the
already-loaded library. Two surface elements. Done.

WHY: per-knob mirroring (`tls_set_alpn(ctx, list)`,
`tls_set_verify(ctx, cb)`, `tls_set_cert(ctx, cert, key)`,
...) explodes the stdlib's surface area linearly with
demand. Each new sandhi/ARK/whatever consumer that needs
something cyrius didn't anticipate becomes a new stdlib
slot — and the stdlib starts encoding library-specific
domain knowledge (what ALPN protocol-list bytes look like,
what the verify callback ABI is) it has no business owning.

The hook approach inverts that: cyrius owns "we have a
TLS connection in progress and you can configure its
SSL_CTX before SSL_new fires". The CONSUMER owns "I want
to set ALPN protocols using SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos with
this specific byte string". `tls_dlsym` lets the consumer
reach the underlying lib's symbol without re-bootstrapping
fdlopen on every call (the stdlib already holds the handle
from `_tls_init`).

CONCRETE SHAPE (v5.6.40):

    fn alpn_hook(user_data, ssl_ctx) {
        var fn_set = tls_dlsym("SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos");
        return fncall3(fn_set, ssl_ctx, &alpn_bytes, 12);
    }
    var tls = tls_connect_with_ctx_hook(fd, host, &alpn_hook, 0);

Stdlib does NOT know what ALPN is. The consumer encodes the
1-byte-length-prefixed protocol list, calls
`SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos` directly via `tls_dlsym`, returns
0/non-zero to signal continue/abort. mTLS is the same shape
with `SSL_CTX_use_certificate_file` + `SSL_CTX_use_PrivateKey_file`.

WHEN TO USE THIS PATTERN: stdlib module wraps a foreign
library where (a) the library's own configuration surface
is wide and growing (OpenSSL, libcurl, libsqlite3,
libuv, ...), and (b) cyrius has no architectural reason to
own the per-knob semantics. Expose handle + hook + dlsym;
let consumers compose.

WHEN NOT TO USE: when cyrius DOES want to own the
semantics (e.g., `lib/syscalls.cyr` deliberately hides
arch differences — exposing a "syscall hook" would
defeat the abstraction).

GENERALIZED API SHAPE for foreign-library stdlib wrappers:

    <module>_<verb>_with_<thing>_hook(args, hook_fp, hook_ctx)
    <module>_dlsym(name) -> fnptr

The default `<module>_<verb>(args)` becomes a 1-line
wrapper passing zeros — no behavior change for existing
callers.

[[entries]]
name = "sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment_violation"
description = "v5.6.41 — SysV ABI requires rsp 16-aligned at every CALL (so callee sees rsp+8 16-aligned at entry). Cyrius's ECALLPOPS for n>6 args used add rsp, 48 unconditionally; for odd nextra (N=7,9,11) this left rsp 8-aligned at CALL, propagating misalignment until something downstream did SSE on a stack-saved value (libssl/libc prologs) and SIGSEGV'd at first instruction. Win64 path was already correct via framesize-mod-15 alignment branch; SysV path missed it."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a cyrius function takes more than 6 formal params,
the 7th+ arg goes on the stack via SysV. For an ODD number of
stack args (N=7, 9, 11), the caller-side push sequence + the
existing `add rsp, 48` cleanup leaves rsp 8-aligned at the
CALL instruction — violating the SysV ABI rule that `(%rsp+8)
must be 16-aligned at function entry`.

The misalignment is silent under cyrius-only call chains
because cyrius prologs don't use SSE. It only surfaces when
something downstream — typically a libssl / libc fn whose
prolog uses `movdqa` / SSE saves on stack-saved values —
faults at its first instruction.

DETECTION: a SIGSEGV reported as "at the first instruction
of an extern symbol" called from a fn with 7+ params is the
canonical signature. Pre-v5.6.41, sandhi's `tls_connect`
from a 7-param `sandhi_conn_open_fully_timed` SIGSEGV'd
inside libssl's prolog — exactly this shape.

ABI MATH: SysV says `(%rsp+8) is 16-aligned at function
entry`. Means `%rsp` itself = 8 mod 16 (the +8 accounts for
the retaddr the CALL just pushed). Means before the CALL,
`%rsp` must be 16-aligned (so retaddr-push leaves it 8-aligned
at entry).

WIN64 vs SysV: Win64's `ECALLPOPS` always allocates
`framesize = 32 (shadow) + nextra*8`, rounded up to 16:

    if ((framesize & 15) != 0) { framesize = framesize + 8; }

That's the alignment branch SysV was missing. SysV's path
emitted `add rsp, 48` regardless, leaving:

    rsp_after_pops = rsp_after_n_pushes + 48
                   = R - N*8 + 48
                   = R - (N-6)*8

For nextra = N - 6:
- nextra = 1: rsp = R - 8 (8-aligned, BAD)
- nextra = 2: rsp = R - 16 (16-aligned, OK)
- nextra = 3: rsp = R - 24 (8-aligned, BAD)
- nextra = 4: rsp = R - 32 (16-aligned, OK)
- nextra = 5: rsp = R - 40 (8-aligned, BAD)

FIX SHAPE: for odd nextra, shift step-2 stack writes from
`[rsp + (6+i)*8]` down to `[rsp + (5+i)*8]` AND change the
final `add rsp, 48` to `add rsp, 40`. This drops one fewer
reg-arg slot, lands the extras at the SAME `[rbp+16+...]`
offsets in the callee from rbp's POV after CALL+push rbp
+mov rbp,rsp, AND keeps rsp 16-aligned at the CALL site.
ECALLCLEAN releases the corresponding 8 bytes of alignment
padding in the symmetric branch.

WRONG FIX (caught by `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` in
v5.6.41 first-attempt): `add rsp, 48; sub rsp, 8` after the
existing logic. This DOES align rsp but moves the stack args
8 bytes higher in the caller frame, so callee reads them at
`[rbp+24]` instead of `[rbp+16]` — alignment fixed, layout
broken. Right answer changes both the writes AND the final
sp-adjust together, so the args land at the same callee-side
offsets while rsp still ends 16-aligned.

DETECTION (codebase-side): grep `ECALLPOPS` and look for any
caller-side calling-convention logic that doesn't have a
parity check on the total arg count. Win64's pattern (always
align to 16 via framesize-mod-15) is the reference.

SELF-HOST FIXPOINT IS NECESSARY BUT NOT SUFFICIENT: cc5's
3-step self-host (cc5_a → cc5_b → cc5_c byte-identical)
verifies codegen DETERMINISM, not codegen CORRECTNESS for
ABI rules cc5 itself doesn't trigger. cc5 callees don't use
SSE in their prologues, so an alignment bug stays latent
until a downstream consumer (sandhi via libssl) hits it.
After any change to ECALLPOPS / ECALLCLEAN /
ESTORESTACKPARM, run `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` AND
`tests/tcyr/sysv_odd_stack_args.tcyr` (which has callers
with 7/8/9/10/11 params hitting an SSE-using leaf).

[[entries]]
name = "pp_ifdef_pass_helpers_must_take_src_base"
description = "v5.6.42 — same-class fix as v5.6.30. PP_IFDEF_PASS copies preprocessed content back to S+0 capped at 524288 B; helpers (PP_HASH/PP_DEFINE/PP_DEFINED/PP_GETVAL/PP_EVAL_IF) reading via S+pos for source > 524288 B land in stale heap. v5.6.30 fixed PP_DERIVE_*; v5.6.42 closed the rest by threading src_base through the family."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: `lex_pp.cyr`'s `PP_IFDEF_PASS` operates on a `tmp`
mmap buffer (full uncapped size, can be up to the 2 MB
preprocess_out limit) but copies the source back to `S+0`
capped at 524288 B (the size of `input_buf`). Helpers that
take a position and read via `load8(S + pos + i)` are
correct for `pos < 524288` but read STALE heap bytes for
`pos >= 524288`.

The bug surfaces as: a `#define` / `#ifdef` / `#if` /
`#derive` directive at offset > 524288 in PP_IFDEF_PASS's
processing gets a wrong hash (PP_HASH reads garbage), so
the directive is misprocessed silently — a name doesn't
get registered, an ifdef block emits when it shouldn't, etc.

v5.6.30 fixed this for `PP_DERIVE_*` (struct-deriving
helpers: serialize, deser, accessors) by threading
`src_base` through the helpers + `PP_PARSE_STRUCT_DEF`.
v5.6.42 closed the rest of the family — `PP_HASH`,
`PP_DEFINE`, `PP_DEFINED`, `PP_GETVAL`, `PP_EVAL_IF` —
which were still using `S + pos` for source reads.

FIX SHAPE:

    # Before:
    fn PP_HASH(S, pos) { ... load8(S + pos + i) ... }
    fn PP_DEFINE(S, pos) { ... }
    # ... etc

    # After:
    fn PP_HASH(src_base, pos) { ... load8(src_base + pos + i) ... }
    fn PP_DEFINE(S, src_base, pos) { ... }   # S kept for flag-table writes at S+0x90800
    # ... etc

CALLERS:
- `PP_PASS` reads from raw input at S+0 → passes `S` as src_base.
- `PP_IFDEF_PASS` reads from the `tmp` mmap buffer → passes `tmp` as src_base.

DETECTION: grep `lex_pp.cyr` for any helper that takes a
`pos` parameter and reads via `load8(S + pos + ...)` or
`load8(S + pos)`. If that helper is called from
`PP_IFDEF_PASS` with a `pos` derived from walking the `tmp`
buffer, it has the same bug.

WHY THE BUG IS LATENT FOR MOST TEST FIXTURES: top-level
`#define` / `#ifdef` / `#if` directives in the source are
caught by `PP_PASS` on the first pass, so they never reach
`PP_IFDEF_PASS`. The bug only triggers when a directive
appears INSIDE included content that PP_PASS doesn't
process (typically nested-include cases that need a 2nd
pass) AND the directive lands past offset 524288 in the
expanded output.

REGRESSION GATE: `tests/tcyr/preprocessor_past_cap.tcyr`
(v5.6.42) exercises the helpers under > 524288 B
expansion. The fix is defensive — even when the test
doesn't trip the latent path, the code shape is now
correct by inspection.

[[entries]]
name = "heap_cap_growth_pattern_compiler_grows_to_fit_language"
description = "v5.6.40 + v5.6.43 — when a stdlib bump or test fixture pushes a compiler cap (preprocessor buffer / output_buf / fixup table / fn count), the right answer is to grow the cap, not trim the stdlib / test / language. Reshuffle methodology: top-down sed substitution + disambiguation discipline for new-addr-equals-old-addr collision points."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a dep bump (patra 1.6.0 → 1.8.3 at v5.6.40,
sigil 2.9.0 → 2.9.3 at v5.6.43) or a test fixture pushes a
compiler-internal cap, the correct response is to grow the
cap. Suggesting that the user trim a stdlib include or test
fixture to fit the existing cap is telling them to
minimize their language because the compiler can't keep up
— that's the wrong direction.

Caps that hit during v5.6.x:
- v5.6.40: preprocess_out 1 MB → 2 MB (patra 1.8.3 +
  full stdlib include set crossed 1 MB by ~280 B on
  large_input.tcyr).
- v5.6.43: output_buf 1 MB → 2 MB (sigil 2.9.3's bigger
  code put `large_input.tcyr` ELF output at ~1.08 MB —
  past the 1 MB cap).

RESHUFFLE METHODOLOGY (proven in v5.6.40, repeated cleanly
in v5.6.43):

1. **Bump the buffer size** at its base offset (e.g.,
   `preprocess_out [1048576]` → `[2097152]`).
2. **Shift every region after** by the delta. Apply
   substitutions TOP-DOWN (highest old offset first)
   to avoid sed collisions.
3. **Update cap-check sites** in `EB` / `EMITELF_*`
   (1048576 → 2097152 in the `if (filesz > ...)` and
   diagnostic strings).
4. **Update the brk syscall arg** in every main_*.cyr.
5. **Update heap-map docs** in main.cyr (authoritative)
   and the 4 main_*.cyr siblings. Watch for stale
   "21.5 MB" / "22.5 MB" total-heap mentions.

DISAMBIGUATION DISCIPLINE — the real cost of the reshuffle:

When NEW(region_A) = OLD(region_B), a global sed can't
tell them apart. v5.6.40 caught five collision points:

1. `var O = S + 0x64A000` was OLD output_buf base; NEW
   codebuf is also 0x64A000. Disambiguation: syntactic
   shape — `var O = S + 0x...;` always means output_buf
   base, while `S + 0x64A000 + cp/coff` means codebuf.
2. `var pfx = S + 0x64A000 + 131072` was OLD output_buf
   tail used as scratch. Comment was the ONLY clue.
3. `0x150B000` was OLD fixup_tbl (16-byte stride),
   NEW ir_cp (4-byte stride). Disambiguation: stride
   in the access pattern.
4. `0x13CA000` was OLD ir_state, NEW ir_blocks.
   Disambiguation: ir_state accessors are bare or
   `+8/+10/+18/+20`; ir_blocks accesses are `+ bi * 32`.
5. `0xECA000` was OLD ir_nodes, NEW struct_fnames.
   Disambiguation: per-file usage — ir.cyr uses 0xECA000
   as ir_nodes; parse_types.cyr uses it as struct_fnames.
   `replace_all` per-file was safe.

ACCEPTANCE CHECK after a reshuffle:

- 3-step self-host fixpoint (`cc5_a → cc5_b → cc5_c → cc5_d`
  byte-identical). Heap shifts are 32-bit immediates →
  byte counts shouldn't change unless the substitution
  chain corrupted something.
- `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` AND
  `tests/tcyr/sysv_odd_stack_args.tcyr` (post-v5.6.41) —
  these exercise calling-convention paths that cc5 itself
  doesn't trip. If a reshuffle subtly broke a code path,
  these gates surface it where self-host wouldn't.
- `tests/tcyr/large_input.tcyr` + `large_source.tcyr` +
  `preprocessor_past_cap.tcyr` — the "include everything"
  fixtures that exercise the new cap end-to-end.

WHY 1 MB → 2 MB AND NOT 4 MB: doubling each cap raise is
the right increment because the next pressure point is
typically 6–18 months out (current dep growth rates).
Going to 4 MB pre-emptively wastes ~15 MB of heap budget
when no consumer needs it. v5.6.40's 1→2 cap raise lasted
3 patches before sigil 2.9.3 needed the next one; v5.6.43's
output_buf raise will likely last longer (output sizes
grow slower than preprocess sizes since codebuf is also
1 MB capped).
"""

